al, posterior and medial compartments, each containing specific muscles, nerves, and blood vessels. The anterior compartment of the lower limb plays a crucial role in certain movements and functions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe anterior compartment of the lower limb is primarily \u003Cstrong\u003Einnervated by the deep fibular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E. This compartment contains muscles such as the tibialis anterior, extensor hallucis longus, and extensor digitorum longus, which are responsible for dorsiflexion of the foot and extension of the toes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContains muscles for plantarflexion of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E - Plantarflexion is primarily performed by muscles in the posterior compartment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupplied by the posterior tibial artery\u003C/strong\u003E - The anterior compartment is supplied by the anterior tibial artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContains muscles for knee flexion\u003C/strong\u003E - Knee flexion is primarily performed by muscles in the posterior compartment of the thigh\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInnervated by the tibial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - The tibial nerve innervates the posterior compartment of the leg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The anterior compartment of the lower limb contains muscles primarily responsible for dorsiflexion of the foot and extension of the toes.","The deep fibular nerve innervates the muscles in the anterior compartment of the lower limb.","The anterior tibial artery supplies blood to the anterior compartment of the lower limb."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. 